[{"_id":"44aba9cb-91ee-35ab-9769-fc26cb58790b","authorName":"Stephen Cleary","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"ad2250182ff26a84dda974e50cd94382","message":"That's a good point. C++ and JS have to use continuation passing style (at best), which is better than what I used for the project in this article (C++ with bare callbacks), but it's not nearly as good as async/await.  \r\n\r\nActually, I expect other languages to follow suit with similar systems (probably just dropping the context capturing and resuming). Python is almost already there with its Twisted library. I hope that a decade from now, every language will have some form of async/await.","postId":"2012_09_an-async-horror-story-d7c3b6f5-6d21-3ef4-b9fd-9d03088d7cf2","replyTo":"","date":"2012-09-14T04:02:09Z","timestamp":1347595329,"authorUserId":""},{"_id":"e6b0d0af-2b78-3642-b5d9-c104222da343","authorName":"svick","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"","message":"Actually, I think the time of monsters is just coming. In WinRT, *everything* is asynchronous, and people are encouraged to use it from C++ or JavaScript (which don't have async/await).  \r\n\r\nAnd there's also [NodeJS](http://dev.hasenj.org/post/31042963934/nodejs-hate).","postId":"2012_09_an-async-horror-story-d7c3b6f5-6d21-3ef4-b9fd-9d03088d7cf2","replyTo":"","date":"2012-09-14T01:23:00Z","timestamp":1347585780,"authorUserId":""},{"_id":"9aa8b679-e8d4-363b-b674-b61fb35db7d8","authorName":"Jorge R. G.","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"","message":"Great story. Very inspiring!","postId":"2012_09_an-async-horror-story-d7c3b6f5-6d21-3ef4-b9fd-9d03088d7cf2","replyTo":"","date":"2012-09-18T11:59:30Z","timestamp":1347969570,"authorUserId":""},{"_id":"5a45be9c-e574-35be-8168-d1b8a6ee3a0c","authorName":"Asynchronous Programming","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"","message":"Lovely Post thanks for sharing the awesome Story..","postId":"2012_09_an-async-horror-story-d7c3b6f5-6d21-3ef4-b9fd-9d03088d7cf2","replyTo":"","